  1. Question

    Curve \(y=f[x]\) contains points \((6,5)\) and \((12,2)\) and \((18,8)\), as shown on the \(x\)-\(y\) plane below.

    plot of chunk unnamed-chunk-1

    In other words: \[f[6]=5\] \[f[12]=2\] \[f[18]=8\]

    Let function \(g\) be a transformation of function \(f\), as defined by the equation below:

    \[g[x]~=~2\cdot f{\left[3\cdot\left(x+2\right)\right]}-4\]

    Find the three corresponding points of curve \(y=g[x]\).

    \(x\) \(g[x]\)


    Solution

    \(x\) \(g[x]\)
    0 6
    2 0
    4 12

    How to get the answers…

    Rewrite the given information: \[f[6]=5\] \[f[12]=2\] \[f[18]=8\] \[g[x]=2\cdot f{\left[3\cdot\left(x+2\right)\right]}-4\]

    1. Use \(f[6]=5\).
      • Set the argument of \(f\) equal to 6. \[3\cdot\left(x+2\right)=6\] Solve the two-step equation. \[x=0\] Substitute 0 for \(x\) in the main equation. \[g[0]=2\cdot f{\left[3\cdot\left(0+2\right)\right]}-4\] Simplify the argument. \[g[0]=3\cdot f{\left[6\right]}-2\] Substitute 5 for \(f[6]\) because \(f[6]=5\). \[g[0]=3\cdot 5-2\] Use arithmetic to evaluate the numerical expression. \[g[0]=6\] So our first new point on \(y=g(x)\) is point \((0,6)\).
    2. Use old point = \((12,2)\). So, use \(f[12]=2\).
      • Set the argument of \(f\) equal to 12. \[3\cdot\left(x+2\right)=12\] Solve the two-step equation. \[x=2\] Substitute 2 for \(x\) in the main equation. \[g[2]=2\cdot f{\left[3\cdot\left(2+2\right)\right]}-4\] Simplify the argument. \[g[2]=3\cdot f{\left[12\right]}-2\] Substitute 2 for \(f[12]\) because \(f[12]=2\). \[g[2]=3\cdot 2-2\] Use arithmetic to evaluate the numerical expression. \[g[2]=0\] So our second new point on \(y=g(x)\) is point \((2,0)\).
    3. Use old point = \((18,8)\). So, use \(f[18]=8\).
      • Set the argument of \(f\) equal to 18. \[3\cdot\left(x+2\right)=18\] Solve the two-step equation. \[x=4\] Substitute 4 for \(x\) in the main equation. \[g[4]=2\cdot f{\left[3\cdot\left(4+2\right)\right]}-4\] Simplify the argument. \[g[4]=3\cdot f{\left[18\right]}-2\] Substitute 8 for \(f[18]\) because \(f[18]=8\). \[g[4]=3\cdot 8-2\] Use arithmetic to evaluate the numerical expression. \[g[4]=12\] So our third new point on \(y=g(x)\) is point \((4,12)\).
